<Base title="Stable Is Not Grounded · Xiaochuan Li"
       description="A strict accuracy–stability–grounding hierarchy, observable only as deep as both sides are transparent."
       showProgress={true}
       toc={true}>
  <article class="prose">
    <div class="text-xs uppercase tracking-wider text-[var(--color-text-dim)] font-medium mb-2">
      Paper 1 · current draft · BlackboxNLP target
    </div>
    <h1>Stable Is Not Grounded</h1>
    <p class="text-[var(--color-text-muted)] italic !text-lg !mb-8">
      A strict accuracy–stability–grounding hierarchy, observable only as deep as both sides are transparent.
    </p>

    <p>
      A model that answers correctly may be doing so for a reason the benchmark never checks. The
      now-standard fix — perturb the input in meaning-preserving ways and see whether the answer
      survives — is one level too shallow. This is the <strong>Certification</strong> leg of the
      program: deciding whether a stable, correct answer is licensed by the structure that grounds the
      conclusion, or by a surface cue that merely correlates with it.
    </p>

    <h2>Roadmap</h2>
    <p>
      The paper reached its current shape through several framings. Each earlier version has its own
      page; the latest progress is below.
    </p>
    <ProgressTimeline items={roadmap} accent="var(--accent-coral)" />

    <h2>The current draft</h2>

    <HeroFigure />

    <p>
      "Correct" answers decompose strictly — <code>accuracy ⊋ stability ⊋ grounding</code> — with every
      containment non-empty. Headline accuracy merges three behaviors that come apart under
      answer-preserving perturbation: unstable, stable-wrong, stable-correct. The standard fix of
      checking stability separates only the first. The residual ambiguity is itself reflexive: a
      stable-correct answer can hold because the model tracks the structure that licenses the
      conclusion, or because it stably rides a shortcut also correlated with the answer at evaluation.
    </p>

    <blockquote>
      Stability is necessary but not sufficient for grounding.
    </blockquote>

    <p>
      The paper is one method carried by two experiments. The method splits the question
      "is this cue irrelevant?" into two parts that must be settled separately: <strong>(a)</strong> is the
      cue causally irrelevant to the answer — fixed <em>before</em> looking at the model, by how the
      item is built or by a linguistic rule; and <strong>(b)</strong> is it correlated with the label in
      training — measured only when the training set is auditable. A cue passing both is a real
      shortcut candidate. We then change it while holding the real structure fixed, alongside a
      pure-noise control, so a drop is the shortcut and not fragility to any edit. This is
      <em>shortcut learning</em> framed as an NLP robustness problem, audited with controls borrowed
      from linguistics — minimal pairs, counterfactual substitution, and a structural decomposition
      of the input variables.
    </p>

    <h3>Experiment 1 — a 91%-accurate model that has learned nothing</h3>

    <p>
      The first experiment runs the full method where everything is auditable. In a controlled
      "can X fly?" setting, a classifier reaches <strong>0.912</strong> accuracy and is
      <strong>stable</strong> under every answer-preserving presentation. By current practice it
      clears both the accuracy bar and the robustness check — and would ship. It was never reading
      the animal. It was reading an irrelevant color feature the training set happened to correlate
      with the label (<code>|r| ≈ 0.81</code>). The demo below lets you push the button that reveals this:
    </p>

    <SCDemo client:load />

    <p>
      Severing that one correlation with a <code>do</code>-intervention drops accuracy by <strong>.408</strong>,
      while a matched pure-noise control moves only <strong>.021</strong> — so the collapse is the
      shortcut, not fragility to any change. On a deployment slice where color no longer tracks the
      label, this model is at chance. Accuracy hid this; the stability check <em>endorsed</em> it.
      This is the <code>SC-spurious</code> bucket. The same verdict structure survives architecture —
      a bag-of-words classifier, a 66M encoder, and a 1.5B decoder (on a two-premise chain variant)
      all collapse under the shortcut sever while the control stays intact.
    </p>

    <h3>Experiment 2 — the same cut, on real grammar</h3>

    <p>
      The synthetic task proves the procedure works; the second experiment asks whether it survives
      contact with a naturally occurring structure. In subject–verb agreement the verb agrees with
      the syntactic <em>subject</em>, not the linearly closest noun — so grammar settles fact
      <strong>(a)</strong> for free: "linear proximity is irrelevant" holds by construction, not by my
      choosing. An <strong>attractor</strong> (an intervening noun of the opposite number) is exactly
      <code>do(class-3)</code>; a same-number intervener is the <code>do(class-2)</code> control. A model
      that holds on both the aligned and attractor slices tracks the subject (<code>SC-grounded</code>);
      one that holds on aligned but collapses on the attractor rides proximity (<code>SC-spurious</code>).
    </p>

    <p>
      Because these are zero-shot pretrained models, fact <strong>(b)</strong> goes dark — the
      proximity–label correlation can't be measured in pretraining — so this is a <em>portability
      diagnosis</em>, not the full certificate Experiment 1 earns. What it buys is a cross-lingual
      flip: the <em>same</em> model, <code>XGLM-564M</code>, rides proximity in English
      (gap <strong>.207</strong>, <code>SC-spurious</code>) but tracks the subject in German
      (gap <strong>.097</strong>, <code>SC-grounded</code>) — the verdict inverts with neither model
      nor task touched, only the language. Toggle the language and add an intervener below:
    </p>

    <AgreementDemo client:load />

    <h3>The decidability boundary</h3>

    <p>
      The deepest cut, <code>SC → {"{grounded, spurious}"}</code>, requires <strong>two-sided observability</strong>:
      the item's ground-truth causal graph must be stipulated by construction (benchmark-side), and
      the candidate shortcut's training correlation must be auditable (model-side). When both sides
      are open the cut is decidable; when either goes dark it is non-identifiable from the available
      observations.
    </p>

    <p>
      <a href="/research/mini-causal-models">MiniCausalLang</a> is built to make that benchmark side
      observable: it compiles linguistic structure into a known causal graph, so the item's
      ground-truth is stipulated by construction and the grounded/spurious cut stays decidable. It is
      the causal-side observability this certification depends on.
    </p>

    <p>
      On a real benchmark with an opaque-pretrained model, the honest decomposition stops at the
      level-two split. Reporting a "causally grounded" fraction there is not a stronger result; it is
      an underdetermined one.
    </p>

    <h3>Status</h3>

    <ul>
      <li><strong>Status:</strong> v5 draft — one method, two experiments. Experiment 1 (fully-auditable synthetic, across TF-IDF, DistilBERT, and a Qwen-1.5B LoRA two-premise arm) and Experiment 2 (subject–verb agreement portability, EN + DE, CLAMS zero-shot) are both run and written. BoolQ (boundary case), HANS (naturalistic shortcut witness), and the multi-seed runs are integrated as appendices. Current work: the reproducibility package and tightening the scope statement.</li>
      <li><strong>Target:</strong> BlackboxNLP @ EMNLP 2026 — workshop / methodological position paper.</li>
      <li><strong>Role in the program:</strong> Paper 1. Establishes the <code>accuracy ⊋ stability ⊋ grounding</code> hierarchy and gives a binary certification protocol for stable-correct behavior under construction-and-auditability assumptions.</li>
      <li><strong>Scope condition:</strong> the grounding verdict is licensed only when the item structure is stipulated <em>and</em> the training entanglement is auditable. Experiment 2 is reported honestly as a portability diagnosis because pretraining is opaque; the method does not solve grounding in the wild.</li>
      <li><strong>Next step:</strong> a <em>fully-licensed</em> agreement experiment — train an agreement model on an auditable corpus so fact (b) becomes measurable, upgrading Experiment 2 from a diagnosis to a full certificate. A complete identification-theoretic treatment is left to future work.</li>
    </ul>

    <hr />

    <p class="!text-sm !text-[var(--color-text-muted)]">
      Code and experiments: <a href="https://github.com/xchuan-li/Stable_is_not_grounded">github.com/xchuan-li/Stable_is_not_grounded</a>.
      Draft available on request — <a href="/contact">/contact</a>.
    </p>
  </article>
</Base>
